A machine is developed that can see the past. (An image is projected of the machine&rsquo;s current location some time in the past.) It operates by splitting photons into pairs of entangled photons, one of which is unstuck in time. Unfortunately, breaking photons into entangled pairs halves their energy; as a result, every time the machine is used, the past becomes more red and less bright.
%
A mathematician engages in an ultimately futile legal battle to make it possible to marry the concept of infinity. In the end, he settles for marrying Cantor&rsquo;s Continuity Conjecture, but after this harrowing experience, he was never the same.
